PHP
---
It stands for PHP Hypertext Preprocessor
The scripts are executed on the server

PHP can:
	1) generate dynamic web content
	2) create, open, read, write, delete and close files on the server
	3) collect form data
	4) send and receive cookies
	5) be used to control user-access
	6) encrypt data
	7) add, delete, modify data in your database

Why PHP:
	1) runs on various platforms
	2) supports almost all servers
	3) supports multiple databases
	4) free, easy to learn, efficient

Interesting facts:
	1) classes, functions, user-defined functions, keywords are case-insensitive
	2) variable names are case-sensitive

echo vs print
	- both can be used with/without parantheses
	- echo has no return value, print has return value of 1
	- echo is slightly faster than print

Data types:
	Strings
		strlen(string), str_word_count(str), strrev(str), strpos(text, pattern) - pos/False
	Integer
	Float
	Boolean
	Array
		sort(array), rsort(array), asort(array) -- sort associative array according to value, ksort(array) -- sort associative array accoring to key, arsort(array), krsort(array)
	Object
	NULL
	Resource

var_dump(variable) - returns data type and value
	int(12), float(12.2), bool(true), string(str.length) "str",
	array(3) { [0]=> int(1) [1]=> int(2) [2]=> int(3) }

Object
	- an object must explicitly be declared like so $myCar = new Car();
	- class Car{
		function Car(){
			$this->model = "XYZ";
		}
	}

NULL
	If a variable is created without a value, it is set to NULL automatically

Resource
	It is the storing of a reference to functions and resources external to PHP

-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Superglobals
	Always accessible, regardless of scope - access from any function, class or file
